Narrative:
On August [XXX], 2025, a Beep-operated Ford E-Transit (002B) equipped with an automated driving system developed by Oxa Autonomy Ltd. was involved in a collision with a stationary object in Jacksonville, FL.
While navigating westbound on [XXX] along a predefined route, vehicle 002B began to slowly veer towards the right curb. The vehicle eventually climbed the curb with the right front and rear wheels and the passenger-side mirror contacted a stationary light pole.
There was one passenger onboard at the time of the incident, an employee of the Jacksonville Transportation Authority. There were no reported injuries, and the vehicle was driven from the scene.
Review of the automated driving system logs as well as onboard video footage determined that the operator disengaged the automated driving system 7.5 seconds prior to the vehicle mounting the curb. Further examination of the onboard video footage noted that the operator appeared to be drowsy and inattentive prior to the incident.
Beep confirmed that the operators shift was in compliance with anti-fatigue policies for this operation. The operator was referred for a post-accident drug and alcohol testing following the incident and tested negative for any impairment. Following the conclusion of the investigation into this incident, the operator was separated from employment.

Narrative:
At approximately 10:55 AM CST on August [XXX], 2025, an Aurora truck was traveling westbound on [XXX] in autonomy during a development mission with an Aurora vehicle operator near Stephenville, Texas. 
The Aurora truck was in the right lane and approaching an unmarked right-lane closure with no advance warning signs. The Aurora vehicle operator decided to disengage autonomy and attempted to manually merge the Aurora truck into the left lane. During the vehicle operators manual lane change, a passing tractor trailer sped up on the left and made contact with the Aurora truck. The Aurora vehicle operator attempted to alert the other tractor trailer of the impact to the Aurora truck by honking the horn and flashing lights. However, the passing tractor trailer proceeded without stopping, and after being unable to gain the other drivers attention, the Aurora vehicle operator pulled over to the shoulder of the highway to assess damage to the Aurora truck. 
The Aurora vehicle operator reported damage to the trucks left side mirror and sensor equipment to Auroras dispatch before returning to Auroras terminal in Aledo, Texas. No injuries were reported.

Narrative: The May vehicle was travelling in an autonomous vehicle (AV) only lane approaching an intersection.  A vehicle travelling to the left of the May shuttle (ego) in the non-AV lane performed a right hand turn across the May vehicles path.  Given the full stopping power and the limited space with which the ego had to stop, the ego was physically unable to stop in time before impact.  The primary factor that led to this collision was human error on the part of the other vehicle that was required to yield to through traffic in the AV lane but did not.  Right turns across a straight lane are uncommon, and drivers are typically not used to them, however there are several signs that instruct other traffic to yield to the vehicles in the AV lane.  There were no autonomy faults or errors which led to this incident.

Narrative: A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was traveling in the left lane on southwest-bound [XXX] toward [XXX] in San Francisco when a ball, immediately followed by a dog, entered the roadway from between parked cars on the left side of [XXX] directly into the path of the Zoox vehicle.  The Zoox vehicle braked in response, but its underbody made contact with the dog.  The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged autonomous mode and brought the vehicle to a stop. The Zoox vehicle operator then reversed the vehicle to free the dog.  The dog owner did not indicate injuries to the dog at the scene. The dog and its owner then returned to the sidewalk and the Zoox vehicle operator drove the vehicle from the scene.  The police were not called.  Zoox subsequently received an email alleging injuries to the dog, "abrasions behind its left front leg and a possible cracked rib."

Narrative: An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was traveling in the right turn lane on southbound [XXX], slowing and preparing to make a right turn onto [XXX] with a green traffic light. At that time, an e-cyclist was traveling south on the sidewalk adjacent to southbound [XXX]. As the Zoox vehicle slowed to execute its turn, the e-cyclist rapidly approached the crosswalk in the path ahead of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked to yield to the approaching e-cyclist. The e-cyclist then veered left and accelerated into the roadway, making contact with the right rear side of the nearly stopped Zoox vehicle. The e-cyclist fell to the ground behind the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then started to move and completed the right turn onto [XXX] and completed its mission. The cyclist appears to have ridden away from the scene. A bystander reported the event to Zoox. There was minor damage to the Zoox vehicle, and information was not exchanged with the e-cyclist. The police were later notified.

Narrative:
On [XXX] at 10:31 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a scooterist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped at the curb facing north on [XXX] for a passenger drop-off when the passenger in the Waymo AV opened the rear right door. As the rear right door was being opened by the passenger, a scooterist that was traveling northbound in the rightmost lane on [XXX] proceeded to pass to the right of the Waymo AV. The left handlebar of the scooter made contact with the open rear right door of the stationary Waymo AV, and the scooterist remained standing after the impact. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The scooterist alleged a minor injury and that the scooter sustained damage. The passenger in the Waymo AV was not belted at the time of the collision, as the passenger was preparing to exit the Waymo AV. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative: The May autonomous vehicle was travelling in an autonomous vehicle (AV) only lane, on [XXX], approaching the intersection at [XXX]  A vehicle travelling to the left of the May shuttle in the non-AV lane attempted to perform a right hand turn across the May vehicles path and collided with the May AV.  The primary factor that led to this collision was human error on the part of the other vehicle that was required to yield to through traffic in the AV lane but did not.  Right turns across a straight lane are uncommon, and drivers are typically not used to them, however there is a metal street sign that instructs other traffic to yield to the vehicles in the AV lane.  There were no autonomy faults or errors which led to this incident.  Additionally, there is a second traffic light at this intersection that warns public drivers to yield to the AV shuttle. This light was not operating as it should during this incident. We are working with our partner to maintain the operation of this light and have implemented a mitigation policy of daily inspections of this light and implementing an AVO in service if this light is not functioning.

Narrative: While traveling north on [XXX], the Autonomous Vehicle Operator (AVO) engages autonomy 3.0 m before the planned right turn and 7.7 m before the break in the curb while traveling at 8.0 m/s.  The May Autonomous Vehicle (ego) was planning to make a tight right turn into a parking lot, which the AVO was unaware of when engaging autonomy.  The ego jerked to the right upon entering autonomy, hitting a curb and damaging both passenger-side front and rear tires and the right rear tire rim.  The AV attempted the right turn despite not having time to slow sufficiently and mounted the curb.  The AVO intervened by accelerating and steering back to the left upon striking the curb, manually maneuvering back to the street while striking a second curb on the opposite side of the parking lot driveway.  Resimulations without the manual intervention show the ego slowing appropriately and making the right turn into the parking lot.  The AVO should have been attentive to the planned route before engaging autonomy.  As a result of this incident, planned improvements to the AVOs instructive dash and audio alerts for upcoming turns have begun to be implemented.

Narrative:
On June [XXX], 2025, a Beep-operated Ford E-Transit (004D) equipped with an automated driving system developed by Oxa Autonomy Ltd. was involved in a collision with a third-party vehicle in Jacksonville, FL. 
While navigating northbound on [XXX], vehicle 004D approached the intersection of [XXX] under automated control. As vehicle 004D proceeded through the intersection, a 2020 Nissan Pathfinder navigating eastbound on [XXX] entered the intersection and struck vehicle 004D on the drivers door. Vehicle 004D had right of way through the intersection with no stop or yield the other vehicle had been stopped at a stop sign prior to the collision. There were no injuries reported at the scene, and both vehicles were driven away from the site of the collision. 
Prior to the collision, the safety operator in vehicle 004D stated that they noticed the other vehicle entering the intersection, applied the vehicles brakes, and steered away from the path of the other vehicle. Though they were able to bring vehicle 004D to a complete stop, they were unable to completely avoid the collision. Review of dashcam footage and of CCTV footage covering the intersection corroborate this narrative. The safety operator was referred for a post-accident drug and alcohol testing after the incident. They tested negative for any impairment. 
Analysis of the ADS logs determined that the ADS had detected the potential collision and had planned an emergency braking action. The safety operators intervention revoked control of the vehicle from the ADS preventing any automated braking actions. 
The [XXX] responded to the accident scene. The driver of the other vehicle was cited for failing to stop at the stop sign, and the JSO CSO noted that vehicle 004D was not at fault for the accident.
